{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"30a95440-f24e-4958-99ff-9e07c9c2ad1f","content":"There's no workflow file in the current directory, so here's general guidance for migrating to NuGet trusted publishing (OIDC):\n\n### 1. Configure NuGet.org\n- Go to **nuget.org → Manage Packages → your package → Trusted Publishers**\n- Add a new GitHub Actions publisher, specifying your **repo owner**, **repo name**, **workflow file name**, and optionally an **environment**\n\n### 2. Update your GitHub Actions workflow\n\n**Remove:**\n- The `NUGET_API_KEY` secret usage\n\n**Add:**\n```yaml\npermissions:\n  id-token: write   # Required for OIDC token request\n  contents: read\n\n# If you configured an environment on nuget.org:\nenvironment: nuget-publish\n```\n\n**Change your push step from:**\n```yaml\n- run: dotnet nuget push **/*.nupkg --api-key ${{ secrets.NUGET_API_KEY }} --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n**To:**\n```yaml\n- run: dotnet nuget push **/*.nupkg --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\nThe OIDC token is exchanged automatically — no API key needed. The `dotnet nuget push` command picks up the trusted publisher credential via the GitHub Actions OIDC token when `id-token: write` is set.\n\n### 3. Cleanup\n- Remove the `NUGET_API_KEY` repository secret once verified\n\nWant me to make these changes to a specific workflow file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"df5ae676-807e-45b9-b1bf-ca1b0134b39c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The directory appears to be empty. There's no existing workflow file to look at. The user is asking a general question about switching from NuGet API key-based publishing to OIDC trusted publishing. Let me provide guidance based on my knowledge.","outputTokens":436},"id":"c57e69c3-0e51-4c04-bb3b-6f49b7a3508d","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:43:44.490Z","parentId":"678803ba-fd44-4ca8-8adc-1ccb4b477bad"}
